::reference id="tensor-numel-card" title="Tensor scalar count" kind="recall-card" reveal="signature-and-concept"

::body
`numel()` answers: how many scalar values does this tensor contain?

Shape `{2, 3, 4}` means:

2 x 3 x 4 = 24

Use `t.numel()` when you need storage size from shape metadata.

Common mistake:
Do not hardcode the final value. Derive it through the tensor API.
::end

::links
anchor="tensor.numel"
file="src/tensor.cpp"
label="Open numel"
::end

::end

::step id="write-numel-step" title="Write shape-to-storage logic"

::explain
A tensor shape is metadata, but runtime allocation needs a scalar count.

You will write the small bridge that multiplies dimensions into storage size.
::end

::edit id="write-numel" path="src/tensor.cpp" mode="append" typing="ghost" anchor="tensor.numel"

::note when="start"
You are about to write the function that converts tensor shape into scalar storage size.
::end

::note when="done"
This tiny function becomes a runtime invariant used by allocation and kernel dispatch.
::end

```cpp

int64_t Tensor::numel() const {
  int64_t total = 1;
  for (int64_t dim : shape_) {
    total *= dim;
  }
  return total;
}
```
::end

::explain focus="tensor.numel"
You just wrote the bridge between shape metadata and actual memory size.

For shape `[2, 3, 4]`, this returns `24`.

This matters later when the runtime allocates hidden states, logits, attention buffers, and KV cache memory.
::end

::end

::step id="use-numel-step" title="Use the tensor API from a smoke path"

::recall id="use-numel" target="main.numel-smoke" references="tensor-numel-card" difficulty="supported-recall"

::task
Create a tensor with shape `{2, 3, 4}` and print its scalar count using the tensor API.
::end

::support
Use the idea you just built.

Relevant API:
`t.numel()`

The expected scalar count for shape `{2, 3, 4}` is `24`.

Do not hardcode `24`; derive it from the tensor.
::end

::verify id="verify-numel" kind="agent"

::goal
Verify that the learner used the tensor API to derive the scalar count for shape `{2, 3, 4}`.
::end

::evidence
files="src/main.cpp src/tensor.cpp include/tensor.hpp"
terminal_command="cmake -S . -B build && cmake --build build && ./build/inferlab --smoke-tensor"
terminal_output="latest"
::end

::rubric
Pass if the implementation demonstrates the relationship between shape and scalar count through the tensor API.

Do not pass if the learner only hardcodes the number 24 without using the tensor API.
Do not pass if the code does not compile.
Do not pass if the runtime output is unrelated or does not provide enough evidence.
::end

::messages
success="Good. You used the tensor API as a real runtime abstraction."
failure="Not quite. Use the reference card and call the tensor scalar-counting API instead of hardcoding the answer."
::end

